embedfield:
Reasons for creating an Index for a string field in MongoDB

When I create an Index on a string-type field in MongoDB I get no significant speed boost from it. In fact, when I use the query:

db.movies.find({plot: /some text/}).explain("executionStats")

An Index is slowing down the query by 30-50% in my Database (~55k Docs).

I know, that I can use a "text" Index, which is working fine for me, but I was wondering, why you would create a "normal" Index on a string field.
answer: The overal idea has not changed. During use, when the application is being executed (mainly, in the Activity), the user will be seeing only a sub-set of informations, therefore, you keep on cheking those that he see, the next expected group, and the previous seen group... this way, suppose a user is cheking movies in a cinema, if the movies are sorted by alphabet, then check current letter + previous letter and next letter.. if its sorted by area, then check cinemas data nearby etc..

Add Mongo TTL Index to Large Collection

I have a large collection in Mongo. Around 1.7 billion records that take up around 5TB of storage space. I no longer need to keep this data indefinitely so I'm looking at options for getting rid of most of the data, preferably based on "createdAt".

I'm wondering what to expect if I add a ttl index to only keep records around for a month at the most. I have the following index currently:

{
        "v" : 1,
        "key" : {
                "createdAt" : 1
        },
        "name" : "createdAt_1",
        "ns" : "someNS.SomeCollection",
        "background" : true
}

How quickly would mongo be able to delete all that data? From what I've read, the ttl process runs every 60 seconds. How much data does it delete each time around?
